04779nam a22006855i 9780226381824DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263818247 a10.7208/97802263818242doi  a(DE-B1597)524480  a(OCoLC)957525226  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aR605b.M954 2017 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a615.5382231 aMukharji, Projit Bihari, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDoctoring Traditions :bAyurveda, Small Technologies, and Braided Sciences /cProjit Bihari Mukharji. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b7 halftones, 9 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrefatory Notes -- tIntroduction. Braiding Science: Refiguring Ayurveda -- tOne. A Baidya-Bourgeois World: The Sociology of Braided Sciences -- tTwo. The Clockwork Body: The Pocket Watch and Machinic Physiospiritualism -- tThree. The Snayubik Man: Reticulate Physiospiritualism and the Thermometer -- tFour. The Chiaroscuric Man: Visionaries, Demonic Germs, and the Microscope -- tFive. Endocrino-Chakric Machine: Hormonized Humors and Organotherapy -- tSix. Baidya-as-Technology: From Diagnosis to Pharmacy in a Bottle -- tConclusion. The Pataphysics of Cosmo-Therapeutics: A Requiem -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLike many of the traditional medicines of South Asia, Ayurvedic practice transformed dramatically in the later nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. With Doctoring Tradition, Projit Bihari Mukharji offers a close look at that recasting, upending the widely held yet little-examined belief that it was the result of the introduction of Western anatomical knowledge and cadaveric dissection. Rather, Mukharji reveals, what instigated those changes were a number of small technologies that were introduced in the period by Ayurvedic physicians, men who were simultaneously Victorian gentlemen and members of a particular Bengali caste. The introduction of these devices, including thermometers, watches, and microscopes, Mukharji shows, ultimately led to a dramatic reimagining of the body. By the 1930s, there emerged a new Ayurvedic body that was marked as distinct from a biomedical body. Despite the protestations of difference, this new Ayurvedic body was largely compatible with it. The more irreconcilable elements of the old Ayurvedic body were then rendered therapeutically indefensible and impossible to imagine in practice. The new Ayurvedic medicine was the product not of an embrace of Western approaches, but of a creative attempt to develop a viable alternative to the Western tradition by braiding together elements drawn from internally diverse traditions of the West and the East.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMedicine, Ayurvedic. 0aMedicine, Oriental. 4aBengal. 4aBritish Empire. 4aIndia. 4aSouth Asia. 4aalternative medicine. 4acomplimentary medicine. 4aeveryday technologies. 4ahealing. 4ahistory of medicine. 4ahistory of science. 4ahistory of technology. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226381824423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226381824.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Packa